    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras face a high-variance schedule today, headlined by **Yordan Alvarez**, who earns our highest score of 87.42 against a vulnerable matchup with Gil. **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a massive 5.74 xERA advantage, providing him the best runway to deliver elite power numbers. While **Yordan Alvarez** sits just outside the 90+ \"Elite\" tier due to park factors, his sustained xwOBA of 0.393 makes him our anchor. Joining him in the strong category is **Junior Caminero** (73.02), who projects to thrive in his #2 spot against Woods Richardson. **Junior Caminero**\u2019s score is inflated by an 11% boost from his SP skill rating and an 8% lineup order bonus, making him our primary source of run production outside of the outfield core.\n\nThe lineup prioritizes high-floor utility to combat the tough rotation of Chris Sale, who presents a hurdle for **Trea Turner** (53.63) and **Kyle Schwarber** (52.28). Despite the difficult matchup, **Trea Turner** remains locked in due to his elite lead-off utility and consistent contribution to our scarcest category, stolen bases. On the bench, **Chase Meidroth** (44.88) was the closest cut from the starting nine; while his #1 spot offers high upside, he was edged out by **Kazuma Okamoto** (55.60), who provides superior total base projection against Cecconi. We are avoiding **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (42.58) today; despite a favorable wind forecast, his efficiency suffers too significantly against the left-handed Wrobleski and an unfavorable #9 hole to warrant a start. \n\nRisk management remains a theme, particularly regarding stolen base opportunities. While **Caleb Durbin** (48.09) and **Victor Scott II** (54.65) are vital for their speed, we are monitoring the opposing pitchers' delivery times closely. **Victor Scott II** in particular carries a high ceiling despite the 4.76 xERA of Hancock, as his speed profile allows him to impact the roto standings even in low-hit scenarios. We are currently tracking 